<!--                 Numerical setup -->
		<section>
		    <section>
                      <hr align="left" width="900" size="5" noshade="noshade">
                      <h3 align='left'> Numerical Setup: Our Model </h3>
                      <hr align="left" width="900" size="5" noshade="noshade">
                      <h4 align="left"> 3D Axisymmetric Compressible euler equations</h4>
                      <p style="font-size:30px">
                      \[ \begin{aligned}
                          \frac{\partial}{\partial t}
                            \left[\begin{array}{c} \rho \\   \rho u_r \\    \rho u_z \\    E   \end{array} \right] 
                        + \frac{\partial}{\partial r} 
                            \left[\begin{array}{c} \rho u_r \\   \rho u_r^2 + p \\    \rho u_r u_z \\     u_r(E+p)   \end{array} \right]
                        + \frac{\partial}{\partial z}
                            \left[\begin{array}{c} \rho u_z \\   \rho u_r u_z \\    \rho u_z^2 + p \\     u_z(E+p)   \end{array} \right] 
                        =   \left[\begin{array}{c} -(\rho u_r)/r \\   -(\rho u_r^2)/r  \\    -(\rho u_r u_z)/r \\     -u_r(E+p)/r   \end{array} \right] 
                        \end{aligned}
                      \]
                      </p>
                      <ul>
                      <br>
                          <li> Good to model acoustic pressure propagation. </li>
                          <li> Nonlinearity allows shock formation. </li>
                          <li> Energy equation provides connection with temperature (relevant for cell damage). </li> <br>
                      </ul>
                         <div class="fragment" style="font-size:40px" data-fragment-index="2">
                        <div class="fragment highlight-red" data-fragment-index="2">
			  <b> 5 variables, 4 equations? <br>
			  Where are the interfaces?</b> 
			</div>  
                        </div>
                    </section>
                    
<!--                     Where are the interfaces -->
                    <section>
                        <hr align="left" width="900" size="5" noshade="noshade">
                        <h3 align='left'> Numerical Setup: Interfaces </h3>
                        <hr align="left" width="900" size="5" noshade="noshade">
                        <p align="left" style="font-size:30px"> The Equation of State (EOS) relates pressure 
                        with density and internal energy to close the system of equations. <br> </br></p>
                        <p style="font-size:30px"> Stiffened gas equation of state (SGEOS) or Tamman EOS: <br> </p>
                        \[
                          p = \underbrace{(\gamma - 1) \rho e }_{\text{Ideal gas}} -\underbrace{\gamma P_{\infty}}_{\text{Stiffening term}}
                          \]
                          <br>
                       <p style="font-size:30px" > Different materials = different parameters for SGEOS</p>
                       <div align='center'>
                        <table border="1" style="font-size:25px;border:solid 3px #000;">
                          <tr>
                          <td style="border:3px solid #000;"> &nbsp Parameter </td>
                          <td style="border:3px solid #000;"> &nbsp $\gamma$ &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp </td>
                          <td style="border:3px solid #000;"> &nbsp $P_\infty$ </td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                          <td style="border:3px solid #000;"> &nbsp Air </td>
                          <td style="border:3px solid #000;"> &nbsp 1.4 </td>
                          <td style="border:3px solid #000;"> &nbsp 0.0 </td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                          <td style="border:3px solid #000;"> &nbsp Water</td>
                          <td style="border:3px solid #000;"> &nbsp 7.15 </td>
                          <td style="border:3px solid #000;"> &nbsp $3\times 10^8$ </td>
                          </tr>
                        </table>
                        <p style="font-size:25px" > Problem can be stiff at interfaces! <br>
                        $\Rightarrow$ Interfaces not trivial to implement. </p>
                       <div>
                    </section>
                    
<!--                     Numerical setup -->
                    <section>
                      <hr align="left" width="900" size="5" noshade="noshade">
                      <h3 align='left'> Numerical Setup </h3>
                      <hr align="left" width="900" size="5" noshade="noshade">
                      Two-Dimensional computational grid
                      <img  src="figsPG/2Drevolve.png" alt="Shocktube" width="500">
                      <ul style="font-size:25pt">
                        <li> Revolved 2D model w/source terms = 3D Axisymmetric model. </li>
                        <li> Air modeled in Eulerian coordinates. </li>
                        <li> Water modeled in Lagrangian coordinates (moving w/fluid). </li>
                        <li> Displacement of material in water small &#8594 Fixed grid</li>
                      </ul>

                    </section>
		</section>
				
<!-- 				Numerical methods -->
		<section>
		
                <section>
                      <hr align="left" width="900" size="5" noshade="noshade">
                      <h3 align='left'> Numerical methods </h3>
                      <hr align="left" width="900" size="5" noshade="noshade">
                      <ul style="font-size:23px">
                      <li>
                        <b> System of 2D hyperbolic conservation laws with source terms. </b> <br>
                        $$\mathrm{1D:} \hspace{7mm} \mathbf{q}_t + \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{q})_x = 0 
                        \hspace{15mm} \mathrm{Cell Average:} \hspace{7mm}
                        Q_i^n = \int_{x_{i-1/2}}^{x_{i+1/2}}\mathbf{q}(x,t_n)dx $$ </li>
                      <li> High resolution finite volume methods (wave propagation). </li>
                            - Godunov method + High Resolution + Limiters <br>
                      <p style="font-size:20px">
                        $$ Q_{i}^{n+1} = Q_i^n - \frac{\Delta t}{\Delta x} 
                        \underbrace{\left[\sum_{p=1}^m(s^p_{i-1/2})^+ W_{i-1/2}^p \right. }_{\mathrm{Left Edge}} +  
                              \underbrace{\left. \sum_{p=1}^m(s^p_{i+1/2})^- W_{i+1/2}^p\right]}_{\mathrm{Right Edge}} 
                              - \underbrace{\frac{\Delta t}{\Delta x}\left(\tilde{F}_{i+1/2} - \tilde{F}_{i-1/2}\right)}_{
                                \mathrm{High Resolution}}
                                                $$ 
                      </p>
                      <li>
                      <p align="left" font-size:23px>
                        Wave formulation: think averaging as updating cell averages with waves coming from the cell edges.
                      </p>
                      </li>
                      </ul>
                       <div style="float:left;width:36%;">
                      <img  src="figsPG/waveform.png" alt="RiemannP" width="350"> <br></br>
                      </div>
                      
                      <!--                       Right Column     -->
                      <div style="float:right;width:63%;font-size:25px;">
                      <br>
                      <p align='left' style="font-size:20px">
                      $$\tilde{F}_{i \pm 1/2} = \frac{1}{2}\sum_{p=1}^{m} |s_{i \pm 1/2}^p |
                            \left(1 - \frac{\Delta t}{\Delta x} |s_{i \pm 1/2}^p| \right) 
                            \underbrace{\tilde{W}_{i \pm 1/2}^p}_{\mathrm{Limiter}}      
                      $$ 
                      On each cell interface, $i-\frac{1}{2}$ and $i+\frac{1}{2}$, we need 
                      those waves. 
                      </p>
                      <div class="fragment" style="font-size:40px" data-fragment-index="2">
                        <div class="fragment highlight-red" data-fragment-index="2">
                          <b> The Riemann problem! </b> 
                        </div>  
                        </div>
                      </div>

                    </section>
                    <section>
                      <hr align="left" width="900" size="5" noshade="noshade">
                      <h3 align='left'> Numerical methods </h3>
                      <hr align="left" width="900" size="5" noshade="noshade">
                        <!--                       Left column -->
                          <div style="float:left;width:46%;">
                            <ul style="font-size:24px">
                            <li> <b> Riemann problem (RP):</b> </li>
                              - conservation law <br>
                              - piecewise constant data w/one discontinuity <br>
                              <li> <b>Riemann solvers: </b></li>
                                  - HLLC approximate solver <br>
                                  - Exact Riemann solver for SGEOS <br> 
                                  - Eulerian/Lagrangian coupling at interface RP <br>
                              <hr align="left" width="450" size="5" noshade="noshade">
                              <li> <b> Additionally: </b> </li>
                                   - Dimensional splitting <br> 
                                   - Fractional step method for source terms with TR-BDF2 <br> 
                                   - Implemented into Clawpack 5.0 
                            </ul>
                          </div>

    <!--                       Right column -->
                          <div style="float:right;width:46%;">
                           <br></br>
                           <img  src="figsPG/RiemannP.png" alt="RiemannP" width="500">
                          </div>
                          <p style="font-size:24px" align="right">
                          Solution of RP for Euler equations
                          </p>

                          <div style="clear: both;"></div>
                    </section>
                  
		</section>
                
